solutions.content:
## Basic Idea
As described in the problem, the Lowest Common Ancestor of a two nodes in a tree is the last common node on the path from the root to p and q. Basically, there can be three cases for a particular node of the tree, depending on the position of p and q relative to it:
1. If p and q are in different subtrees of the node. (For eg p is in left subtree and q is in right subtree, and vice versa).
2. If either of p and q is equal to the node.
3. If p and q are in the same subtree of the current node. (For eg both p and q are in left subtree, or right subtree).

We will return the current node as the LCA for cases 1 and 2, and recursively call the LCA function on the corresponding subtree for case 3.

So for implementing the solution, we need two functions, one main function for finding the LCA, and one auxiliary function for finding the positions of p and q in the subtrees.
<br>
## Approach 1: Full Recursion (Accepted but very slow)
The most naive approach would be to go full recursion on this, from the find function to the LCA function.
```
bool find(TreeNode *root, TreeNode *toFind) {
	if(!root) return false;
	if(root != toFind) {
		return find(root->left, toFind) || find(root->right, toFind);
	}
	else {
		return root;
	}
}
TreeNode* lowestCommonAncestor(TreeNode* root, TreeNode* p, TreeNode* q) {
	if(!root) return nullptr;
	// four cases
	if(find(root->left, p)) {
		if(find(root->right, q)) {
			//root is LCA
			return root;
		}
		else if(find(root->left, q)){
			//both are in one subtree
			return lowestCommonAncestor(root->left, p, q);
		}
		else {
			//root is q;
			return root;
		}
	}
	else if(find(root->right, p)){
		if(find(root->left, q)) {
			//root is LCA
			return root;
		}
		else if(find(root->right, q)){
			//both are in same subtree
			return lowestCommonAncestor(root->right, p, q);
		}
		else {
			//q is root
			return root;
		}
	}
	else {
		//p is root;
		//no matter where q is, p is LCA
		return p;
	}
}
```
![Runtime and Memory usage: Approach 1](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/63373146-7220-447c-bb62-50f528dfc4a2_1621654422.2065408.png)

**Complexity**

Time: O(n) (proved at the end)
Space: O(n)
As you can see, this solution barely passed, so it will certainly not cut it.
<br>

## Approach 2: Optimize Most Called Recursive Function

The next step would be to optimise our most called recursive function (i.e find()).
As the recursion of find() is not tail recursion (i.e only one recursive call per function call), we can't eliminate the stack completely, hence we still have to use a stack to keep track of the roots of the subtrees being processed. However, we save a little on space by using this approach (although not asymptotically) by eliminating the program stack from the picture.

```
bool find(TreeNode *root, TreeNode *toFind) {
	if(!root) return false;
	stack<TreeNode *> nodes;
	nodes.push(root);
	while(!nodes.empty()) {
		TreeNode *curr = nodes.top();
		nodes.pop();
		if(curr == toFind) return true;
		if(curr->left) nodes.push(curr->left);
		if(curr->right) nodes.push(curr->right);
	}
	return false;
}
```

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/ba239023-ff4b-4c99-95b9-98967c04f95c_1621655084.0239727.png)

**Complexity**
Same as previous solution
<br>

## Approach 3: Some Observations and Complete Iteration
We can clearly see that the recursion in our main LCA function is tail recursion, since there is only one recursive call from the function per run. Hence it can be easily converted to iteration, without even using a stack, we just modify the root variable directly for each subcall.
Also, some optimizations we can make are:
1. Check if p or q is the root first, then we don't even need to call the find() function, and the answer is root, no matter what.
2. Make subcases based on whether the left and right subtree of the current node exist, to avoid making calls to find() with an empty subtree.

This way, we can minimize the number of calls to our costly function (O(n)) and thus save on runtime a little (again, not asymptotically).
Hence the worst case for this algorithm would be very difficult to reach, and the average case performance would be good.

```
bool find(TreeNode *root, TreeNode *toFind) {
	if(!root) return false;
	stack<TreeNode *> nodes;
	nodes.push(root);
	while(!nodes.empty()) {
		TreeNode *curr = nodes.top();
		nodes.pop();
		if(curr == toFind) return true;
		if(curr->left) nodes.push(curr->left);
		if(curr->right) nodes.push(curr->right);
	}
	return false;
}
TreeNode* lowestCommonAncestor(TreeNode* r, TreeNode* p, TreeNode* q) {
	TreeNode *root = r;
	while(root) {
		// four cases
		if(root == p) return p;
		else if(root == q) return q;
		if(root->left) {
			if(root->right) {
				if(find(root->left, p)) {
					if(find(root->left, q)) {
						root = root->left;
					}
					else {
						return root;
					}
				}
				else {
					if(find(root->right, q)) {
						root = root->right;
					}
					else {
						return root;
					}
				}
			}
			else {
				//no right child
				root = root->left;
			}
		}
		else {
			//no left child
			if(root->right) {
				root = root->right;
			}
			else {
				//error
				return nullptr;
			}
		}
	}
	return nullptr;
}
```

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/6b5bf1ef-2316-4aab-b715-ab8a34761c52_1621655611.5542002.png)

**Complexity**
Time:  O(n) (proved below)
Space: O(n)

**Upvote** if you liked this post, and feel free to ask any doubts, or suggest any corrections/improvements in the comments.
I'm also a learner like everyone here, so if you find a mistake in this post, please point it out.

**Edit:**
I just did a thorough analysis of the time complexity of my solution, and found out that it should be O(n), not O(nlogn) (:D). Sorry for any confusion caused by this. :(

Here is the proof for the same:
Starting from the root, we make two calls of find (one for each subtree) so a total of O(n) operations here. Then we either return the result, or in the worst case, have to recurse further, to either the left or right subtree (only one of those). So the number of nodes is halved on average.
Hence the next step costs O(n/2) and so on.
Thus in the case of a mostly balanced tree, the total complexity is:
```n + n/2 + n/4 + .... + 1 = n (2 - 1/n) ``` (by Geometric Progression)
 i.e O(2n - 1) ~ **O(n)**.

 Now for the case of skewed trees. Let's assume that the tree is reduced to a linked list on the right. (i.e no nodes have left child). 
 In this case, we don't even call find function, because we are bound to reach a situation where either of p or q is the root and the other is its right child.
 Hence the complexity in this case is similar to that of traversing a linked list i.e **O(n)**.

 Since all possible cases fall between these two extremes, the complexity is **O(n)**

 Hence the time and space complexity of the same is O(n).

