## Approach
We can do a DFS search in the tree to locate our two nodes, the node which receives some kind of non-null result from its left and right searches will be the lowest ancestor of the required nodes. If we don't get non-null response from both left & right subtree then we just return the result as it is.

## Complexities
**Time: O(n)
Space: O(h)**

## Code
```
class Solution {
    public TreeNode lowestCommonAncestor(TreeNode root, TreeNode p, TreeNode q) {
        if(root == null) return null;
        if(root == p || root == q) return root;
        TreeNode left = lowestCommonAncestor(root.left, p, q);
        TreeNode right = lowestCommonAncestor(root.right, p, q);
        if(left != null && right != null) return root;
        return left == null ? right : left;
    }
}
```

