solutions.content:
Relative positions of p and q help divide the problem.

There are three relative positions of p and q to root:
- Both p and q are to the right of root, then the LCA exists in root's right subtree.
- Both p and q are to the left of root, then the LCA exists in root's left subtree.
- p and q are one to the left, the other to the right of root, then the LCA is root.

However, we can't tell relative postitions of p and q at first, so postorder traversal is needed. Meanwhile, one more base case is needed: when we exhaust the tree, i.e. when root is null.

****
```
class Solution:
    def lowestCommonAncestor(self, root: 'TreeNode', p: 'TreeNode', q: 'TreeNode') -> 'TreeNode':
        if root is None or root == p or root == q:
            return root

        left = self.lowestCommonAncestor(root.left, p, q)
        right = self.lowestCommonAncestor(root.right, p, q)

        if left is not None and right is not None:
            return root
        elif left is not None:
            return left
        elif right is not None:
            return right
        else:
            return None
```

